<h1>Problem 14</h1>
    <a href="../amc10b-2025.html">← Back to AMC 10B 2025</a>

<div class="section">
    <div class="info-row">
        <b>Category:</b> <span>Combinatorics</span>
    </div>
</div>
<p>Nine athletes, no two of whom are the same height, try out for the basketball team. One at a time, they draw a wristband at random, without replacement, from a bag containing $3$ blue bands, $3$ red bands, and $3$ green bands. They are divided into a blue group, a red group, and a green group. The tallest member of each group is named the group captain. What is the probability that the group captains are the three tallest athletes?</p>
<div class="options">
$$\textbf{(A) } \frac{2}{9} \qquad \textbf{(B) } \frac {2}{7} \qquad \textbf{(C) } \frac{9}{28}\qquad \textbf{(D) } \frac{1}{3} \qquad \textbf{(E) } \frac{3}{8}$$
</div>
<div class="section">
    <div class="info-row">
        <b>Difficulty:</b> <span>32/100 - A straightforward and intuitive probability problem. </span>
    </div>
    <div class="info-row">
        <b>Core Concepts:</b> <span> probabilities. </span>
    </div>
    <div class="info-row">
        <b>Challenges:</b> <span> The problem can appear as intimidating despite the simplicity of what it is truly asking. </span>
    </div>
    <div class="info-row">
        <b>Techniques:</b> <span> The condition more bluntly states that the three tallest members much each pick different color bands. From here, a probabilistic argument can be used. </span>
    </div>
    <div class="info-row">
        <b>Error-prone Steps:</b> <span> Many competitors did not realize that the remaining amount of players decreased by $1$ as they got selected.  </span>
    </div>
    <div class="ideal-time">
        <b>Ideal Time:</b>
        <div class="ideal-list">
            Experienced: ≤ 1 min<br>
            Intermediate: ≤ 2-3 min<br>
            Beginner: ≤ 4 min
        </div>
    </div>
</div>
